hands_on_practices.problem:
A homogeneous, small-strain, linearly elastic, orthotropic lamina is tested under in-plane (plane-stress) loading with its material axes aligned to the test axes. The independent engineering constants under plane stress are $E_1$, $E_2$, $\nu_{12}$, and $G_{12}$. Assume the existence of a strain energy density so that the elastic operator is linear, invertible, and symmetric. You can apply spatially uniform in-plane stress states ($\sigma_1, \sigma_2, \tau_{12}$) and, depending on the instrumentation selected, measure some subset of the in-plane strain components ($\varepsilon_1, \varepsilon_2, \gamma_{12}$). All loads and measurements are noiseless, and stress magnitudes are known exactly.

Which of the following experimental programs is sufficient to uniquely identify all independent plane-stress engineering constants of the lamina? Select all that apply.

- A. Perform: 
  - one uniaxial normal stress test in direction $1$ with ($\sigma_1 \neq 0, \sigma_2=0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring only $\varepsilon_1$; 
  - one pure in-plane shear test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2=0, \tau_{12} \neq 0$), measuring only $\gamma_{12}$; 
  - one equal-biaxial normal stress test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2 \neq 0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring only $\varepsilon_1$.

- B. Perform:
  - one uniaxial normal stress test in direction $1$ with ($\sigma_1 \neq 0, \sigma_2=0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring both $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$;
  - one uniaxial normal stress test in direction $2$ with ($\sigma_1=0, \sigma_2 \neq 0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring both $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$;
  - one pure in-plane shear test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2=0, \tau_{12} \neq 0$), measuring $\gamma_{12}$.

- C. Perform:
  - one uniaxial normal stress test in direction $1$ with ($\sigma_1 \neq 0, \sigma_2=0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring both $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$;
  - one pure in-plane shear test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2=0, \tau_{12} \neq 0$), measuring $\gamma_{12}$.

- D. Perform:
  - one nontrivial biaxial normal stress test with ($\sigma_1 \neq 0, \sigma_2 \neq 0, \tau_{12}=0$), measuring both $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$;
  - one pure in-plane shear test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2=0, \tau_{12} \neq 0$), measuring $\gamma_{12}$.

- E. Perform:
  - two distinct biaxial normal stress tests with ($\sigma_1^{(j)}, \sigma_2^{(j)}$) for $j \in \{1,2\}$ such that ($\sigma_1^{(1)}, \sigma_2^{(1)}$) is not a scalar multiple of ($\sigma_1^{(2)}, \sigma_2^{(2)}$), both with $\tau_{12}=0$, measuring both $\varepsilon_1$ and $\varepsilon_2$ in each test;
  - one pure in-plane shear test with ($\sigma_1=\sigma_2=0, \tau_{12} \neq 0$), measuring $\gamma_{12}$.

Answer choices are mutually independent; more than one may be correct.
